<div class="section">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="small-12 large-12 columns">
      <%= image_tag 'subway.jpg', class: 'big_day_photo-right', align: 'right' %>
      <p>
        <h2>Transportation in NYC</h2>
      </p>
      <h3>Subway</h3>
      <p>
        <span class="bold">Fares</span> - $2.75 per ride regardless of distance or $31 for unlimited rides for 7 days. <a href="http://web.mta.info/metrocard/" target="_blank">Metrocard</a> is a reusable and refillable card needed to enter the subway. New cards have a $1 charge but can be shared legally if you pay per ride. To share a card, the first person swipes and enters and gives it to the next person who swipes and enters. 
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="bold">Navigation</span> - Newer subway cars list and call out stops while older ones do not and require one to pay attention to the station signs. Downtown trains or trains going to Brooklyn are going south. Uptown trains or trains going to Queens are going North. 
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="http://web.mta.info/maps/submap.html" target="_blank">Map</a> - As a rule of thumb, it usually takes 2 minutes to the next stop. 
      </p>
      <h3>Uber</h3>
      <p>
        For those unfamiliar with Uber, it is an app that you download on your iPhone or Android device. After downloading, the app will direct you how to use it. If it is your first ride, you can enter the following code (59ec9) to get a discount off your ride. (Full disclosure - we get a discount if you use this code). It does not work if you do not have a suitable device. For fare estimates<a href="https://www.uber.com/cities/new-york/?int=a" target="_blank">click here</a>. 
      </p>
      <h3>Taxi</h3>
      <p>
        New York City does not charge fees to use a credit card and drivers expect 20% gratuity. Cabs can be hailed from the street. 
      </p>
      <h3>Walking</h3>
      <p>
         New York is very walkable and each block only takes about a minute to walk. 
      </p>
      
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
